{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17609141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17609141"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:41:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:41:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16089"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16089","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16089"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.55,0.32,0.09,0,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8780"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71577"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8780"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16089"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57073"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1359"},{"type":"tags","id":"1465"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"1858"},{"type":"tags","id":"2451"},{"type":"tags","id":"4025"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20967"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20970"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71577"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman at 32 weeks gestation presents following a motor vehicle accident. She has a history of smoking and cocaine use. She appears pale and diaphoretic with severe abdominal pain. Her vital signs show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EBlood pressure: 85/50 mmHg\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHeart rate: 125 beats/minute\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERespiratory rate: 24 breaths/minute\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECardiotocography shows fetal bradycardia. There is minimal vaginal bleeding noted on examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Complete placental abruption with concealed hemorrhage","Partial placental abruption with apparent hemorrhage","Placenta previa","Placenta accreta","Vasa previa"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete placental abruption with concealed hemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with severe abdominal pain, shock, and fetal distress despite minimal external bleeding. The blood collects between the separated placenta and uterine wall. Risk factors include trauma, smoking, and cocaine use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPartial placental abruption with apparent hemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E would show significant vaginal bleeding. \u003Cstrong\u003EPlacenta previa\u003C/strong\u003E presents with painless vaginal bleeding. \u003Cstrong\u003EPlacenta accreta\u003C/strong\u003E is abnormal placental attachment typically diagnosed on ultrasound and associated with previous caesarean sections. \u003Cstrong\u003EVasa previa\u003C/strong\u003E presents with painless vaginal bleeding when fetal vessels passing near the cervix, unprotected by the umbilical cord or placental tissues rupture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of shock, severe pain, minimal external bleeding, and fetal distress strongly suggests complete placental abruption with concealed hemorrhage. The presence of multiple risk factors (trauma, smoking, cocaine use) supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Placental abruption is the premature separation of the placenta from the uterine wall, commonly associated with trauma, hypertension, smoking and cocaine use.","Complete placental abruption with concealed hemorrhage presents with severe pain, shock and fetal distress but minimal external bleeding."],"references":["Brandt JS, Ananth CV. Placental abruption at near-term and term gestations: pathophysiology, epidemiology, diagnosis, and management. Am J Obstet Gynecol. 2023 May;228(5S):S1313-S1329. doi: 10.1016/j.ajog.2022.06.059. Epub 2023 Mar 23. PMID: 37164498; PMCID: PMC10176440.","Giordano R, Cacciatore A, Cignini P, Vigna R, Romano M. Antepartum haemorrhage. J Prenat Med. 2010 Jan;4(1):12-6. PMID: 22439054; PMCID: PMC3263934.","Oguejiofor CB, Okafor CD, Eleje GU, Ikechebelu JI, Okafor CG, Ugboaja JO, Ogabido CA, Njoku TK, Umeononihu OS, Okpala BC, Nwankwo ME, Ezeigwe CO, Enechukwu CI, Eke AC. A Five-Year Review of Feto-Maternal Outcome of Antepartum Haemorrhage in a Tertiary Center. Int J Innov Res Med Sci. 2023 Mar;8(3):96-101. doi: 10.23958/ijirms/vol08-i03/1637. Epub 2023 Mar 16. PMID: 37006445; PMCID: PMC10066273."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57073"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16089"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57073"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-19T17:02:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T21:09:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8780"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71577"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading